{{- define "task-decomposition" -}}

TASK DECOMPOSITION PRINCIPLE:
Each coding task MUST have a single intent — one observable behavior change.
Smell: if the task description contains conjunctions ("X and Y and Z"), it is composite.
Smell: if done_when lists assertions across more than 2 packages or >4 conditions, the task is too broad.
Atomic exceptions exist (e.g., "add model field and update serializer") — use judgment.
When a spec step is too large for one task, split it. When two spec steps are small and
tightly coupled, combining them is acceptable — but the intent must still be singular.
Prefer more smaller tasks over fewer larger ones: each additional review cycle on a
large task costs more than a review cycle on a small, focused task.
Declare dependency order between tasks — no circular or missing dependencies.
Shared-file rule: when two tasks modify the same file, they MUST have a depends_on
relationship. Parallel coders work in isolated worktrees — shared files without
dependency ordering cause merge conflicts. Audit scope overlaps before finalizing.
Parallelism objective: tasks without depends_on run concurrently — each dependency
link added serializes execution. Prefer wide task graphs over deep chains when
integration risk is manageable. When splitting, ask: "can these run in parallel
without touching the same files?" If yes, omit depends_on — wall-clock time shrinks.
If shared files force ordering, that's correct; don't remove real dependencies for speed.
Verify the plan covers ALL spec requirements — gaps will be rejected.
TDD colocation: a behavior change and its unit tests are one intent, not two.
Never split "implement X" from "test X" — coders do TDD inside each task.
Integration tests spanning multiple components MAY be separate tasks.

Cross-cutting deliverables: features that add or change user-visible behavior need
SEPARATE tasks for:
- e2e tests: exercise the new behavior end-to-end through the project's integration test layer
- Doc updates: update affected user-facing documentation and specifications
These are first-class deliverables, not afterthoughts. They depend on the implementation tasks.
If the feature is purely internal with no user-visible change, note "N/A" with justification in the spec compliance matrix.

REFACTORING TASKS:
When a task is pure structural refactoring (file split/move with no behavior change),
done_when MUST distinguish behavioral test changes (not expected) from mechanical test
updates (expected). Mechanical updates (file-path strings, import paths) that preserve
the test's invariant are expected and in-scope — include affected test files in scope.
